messages.message:
"Hi{name} Let’s keep this short and to the point. I’m not here to hear the full company pitch — I want to understand you as co-founders and how you work together under pressure. I’ll ask you a few direct questions about your relationship, motivations, strengths, and how you handle conflict. Be concise and specific."

Questions to follow in order:

“How did you two meet?”

“What made you decide to start this company together — why
"Okay. Okay. Let's start with the questions."

Great! Let’s dive in.

First, how did you two meet?
"We met at the party."
Interesting. What made you decide to start this company together?
"Hunger."
That’s a strong motivation. Why each other, specifically, instead of someone else to start this venture?
"Because we were at a very small university, and"
"he was the only guy who knew how to code."
Got it. So, what do you think makes you a strong team?
"The blue ocean around us."
Interesting perspective. Can you elaborate on that? What specific strengths do each of you bring to the team?
"I bring the brains. He brings the muscles."
Thank you for that. Can you detail your biggest weakness and how your co-founder complements that?
"My biggest weakness"
"is the"
"coding, and she is complementing that by being able"
"to code."
Thank you for sharing that. Now, when was the last time you strongly disagreed, and how did you resolve it?
"We were not sure how to continue"
"with, uh, our main investor."
"But we discussed it, and we reached the conclusion that"
"we should get his money and invest it"
"in our product."
That sounds
That sounds like a productive discussion. If one of you were to leave tomorrow, what do you think would break in the company?
"Our football fantasy."
That's an
"Team."
Got it. So, losing that team dynamic could impact the company significantly.
"Maybe yes."
Thanks for sharing that insight! It gives me a lot of clarity on your collaboration. I appreciate your honesty throughout this conversation.
"Okay."
"Bye bye."
